        <div xml:id="AN181.2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">iṭaiccurat toḻiyak karutiya neñciṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What was said to the heart that intended to stay behind in the middle of the desert.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN181.2">
      <lg type="edition">
        <l>tuṉṉaruṅ kāṉamun tuṇita lāṟṟāy</l>
        <l>piṉṉiṉṟu peyarac cūḻntaṉai yāyi</l>
        <l>ṉeṉṉilai yuṟaimō neñcē yoṉṉā</l>
        <l>rōmparaṇ kaṭanta vīṅkuperun tāṉai</l>
        <l>yaṭupō<supplied>r</supplied> mi<supplied>ñi</supplied>li ce<supplied>ruvē</supplied>l kaṭaii</l>
        <l>murukuṟaḻ muṉpoṭu porukaḷañ civappa</l>
        <l>vāa yeyiṉaṉ vīḻnteṉa ñāyiṟ</l>
        <l>ṟoṇkati ruruppap putaiya vōrāṅku</l>
        <l>vampap puḷḷiṉ kampalai peruntōṭu</l>
        <l>vicumpiṭai tūra vāṭi mocintuṭaṉ</l>
        <l>pūviri yakaṉṟuṟaik kaṉaivicaik kaṭunīrk</l>
        <l>kāvirip pēryāṟ ṟayirkoṇ ṭīṇṭi</l>
        <l>yekka riṭṭa kuppai veṇmaṇal</l>
        <l>vaippiṉ yāṇar vaḷaṅkeḻu vēntar</l>
        <l>ñāla nāṟu nalaṅkeḻu nallicai</l>
        <l>nāṉmaṟai mutunūṉ mukkaṭ celva</l>
        <l>ṉāla muṟṟaṅ kaviṉpeṟat taiip</l>
        <l>poykai cūḻnta pōriṉmaṇ makaḷir</l>
        <l>kaicey pāvait tuṟaikka ṇiṟukku</l>
        <l>makara neṟṟi vāṉṟōy puricaic</l>
        <l>cikaran tōṉṟāc cēṇuyar nalliṟ</l>
        <l>pukāar naṉṉāṭ ṭatuvē pakarvarp</l>
        <l>paṇṭa nāṟum vaṇṭā ṭaimpāṟ</l>
        <l>paṇaittakait taṭaiiya kāmpiṉ meṉṟō</l>
        <l>ḷaṇaṅkucā larivai yirunta</l>
        <l>maṇaṅkamaḻ maṟukiṉ maṇaṟperuṅ kuṉṟē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        <l>You who cannot resolve [on passing] even the forest difficult to approach, (1)</l>
        <l>if you plan on staying behind [and] returning, (2)</l>
        <l>stay in my position, heart!  (3a-c)</l>
        <l>It is in the good land of Pukāar, (22a-c)</l>
        <l>with good houses high from a distance that will not appear over the tops (21)</l>
        <l>of the sky-touching fortifications with makara fronts, (20)</l>
        <l>where in the ghat area stay the dolls made by the hands (19)</l>
        <l>of girls from the embattled earth surrounded by ponds (18)</l>
        <l>tying [them] beautifully, in Ālamuṟṟam (17)</l>
        <l>of the three-eyed lord of the ancient treatises of the four Vedas, (16)</l>
        <l>of good fame that pervades the world, (15)</l>
        <l>[belonging to] kings prosperous with the fertility of the region (14)</l>
        <l>of white sand in heaps that are deposited in dunes, (13)</l>
        <l>gathering together the fine sand of the big river Kāviri, (12)</l>
        <l>[her] water swift with intense speed by the vast ghat where flowers expand, (11)</l>
        <l>as [there] swarm together in play, so that the middle of the sky is full, (10)</l>
        <l>clamouring big multitudes of new birds, (9)</l>
        <l>like one to be enveloped by the heat of the bright rays (8)</l>
        <l>of the sun, because Āay, the hunter has fallen (7)</l>
        <l>while the battlefield turns red as with the strength of Muruku (6)</l>
        <l>Miñili of murderous fight driving [his] battle spear, (5)</l>
        <l>with a swelling big army that crossed the fortress protected by the enemies, (3df.)</l>
        <l>– the big hill of sand, [its] streets fragrant with scent, (26)</l>
        <l>where the much tormenting young woman is, (25)</l>
        <l>[her] soft shoulders like befitting, plump stalks of bamboo, (24)</l>
        <l>with [her hair in] five parts in which bees play, fragrant of traders’ goods. (22df.)</l>
      </lg>
